title: ‘Terrible deal’: Expert unpacks Trump’s proposed Russia-Ukraine peace deal
description: The Australian's Foreign Editor Greg Sheridan says the Biden administration, the Trump administration and the Europeans have not given Ukraine enough weapons and money to get an advantage over Russia.   “This is a terrible deal that Trump has proposed … it shows how really pathetic the West has been in its support of Ukraine,” Mr Sheridan told Sky News host Andrew Bolt.  “The Biden administration, then the Trump administration, and the Europeans have never given the Ukrainians the weapons and the money they need to get a decisive advantage.”

title: Liberal leadership in question as Taylor and Hastie solidify their place as alternatives
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson examines the Liberal Party’s future leadership, with Angus Taylor and Andrew Hastie as the alternatives.  “It is now a matter of time for Sussan Ley, the only question is whether the next leader will be Angus Taylor or Andrew Hastie,” Ms Markson said.  “Whether the Liberals sort their leadership out now or early in the new year, it is only a matter of time.”

title: EXCLUSIVE: Albanese government may bench Chris Bowen over COP31 president role
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson says there are discussions currently occurring within the Albanese government about whether Energy Minister Chris Bowen should step aside from his position.  “I can reveal there are discussions unfolding inside the Albanese government about whether Chris Bowen should step aside as energy minister, to be replaced by star performer, Andrew Charlton,” Ms Markson said.  “It comes after Bowen was appointed the president of negotiations for the COP 31 summit, to be held in Turkey next year.  “Now, Chris Bowen will not want to step down, and he’ll likely be arguing that he can do both roles. And he may prevail in this quest.”

title: Democratic Party filled with ‘Marxist-style revolutionaries’ with aim of toppling order
description: Newsweek Senior Editor-at-Large Josh Hammer says the Democratic Party is filled with “revolutionaries” who hold Marxist-style beliefs.  “These are radicals … with very, very few exceptions,” Mr Hammer told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “Their party … is filled with revolutionaries, with genuine Marxist-style revolutionary insurgents who are here to topple the established order.”

title: Chris Bowen ‘sold Australia out’ in Brazil to stop coal and gas
description: Sky News host Andrew Bolt slams Climate and Energy Minister Chris Bowen claiming he has betrayed Australia.  Mr Bolt said Mr Bowen “sold us out” in Brazil as the energy minister signed a deal to tell the world to stop buying Australia’s biggest coal and gas exports.  The Labor minister also promised to get rid of Australia’s coal and gas generators which supply two-thirds of the country’s electricity.

title: ‘Quintessential left-wing commentator’ Jake Tapper under fire for military comments
description: Newsweek Senior Editor-at-Large Josh Hammer criticises CNN anchor Jake Tapper’s rhetoric concerning members of the military and their supposed complicity in committing crimes.  “Jake Tapper is a quintessential Trump deranged syndrome left-wing commentator in the United States,” Mr Hammer told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “You play with absolute fire when you start to play with that. If there is an order that you are ordered to do that for whatever reason, you genuinely feel like you cannot do, there are remedies available for you.”

title: ‘What could possibly go wrong?’: Swalwell’s desire to implement mobile phone voting scrutinised
description: Newsweek Senior Editor-at-Large Josh Hammer says Eric Swalwell’s desire to enable voting by mobile cell phone will only provide an “additional layer of insecurity”.  “As far as the notion of voting by phone, frankly, I think that America’s elections are insecure enough as is, I would not be one to necessarily want to add an additional layer of insecurity,” Mr Hammer told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “What could possibly go wrong by relying on AT&T, Verizon and various mobile cell phone providers to cast your vote?”

title: Trump’s peace deal under fire over Ukraine’s territorial concessions
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada says Ukraine would have to accept territorial concessions in US President Donald Trump's peace proposal as Russia deems the agreement “cautiously favourable”.   “This plan … is there are full territorial concessions that Ukraine would have to accept, and that Russia gets to keep,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Sharri Markson.   “While Ukraine would have to renounce NATO membership, which was a big point throughout this saga, they would receive Western-backed security guarantees.  “Russia is reportedly cautiously favourable to the framework.”

title: ‘Ukraine’s going to have to give up territory’: Trump’s Ukraine peace deal analysed
description: Newsweek Senior Editor-at-Large Josh Hammer analyses the Ukraine peace deal orchestrated by US President Donald Trump, saying Ukraine is going to have to give up territory regardless.  “The broad outlines of it are something that I couldn’t see myself getting behind,” Mr Hammer told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “Ukraine’s going to have to give up territory … it’s not going to gain back territory.”

title: ‘Turn off your phone, get off the internet’: China chairman visits Parliament House
description: On tonight’s episode of Paul Murray Live, Sky News host Paul Murray discusses Pauline Hanson’s burqa stunt, cost of living, US politics and more.

title: ‘Huge gulf’: Aussies to pay more tax under Labor government
description: Sky News host Paul Murray highlights how Aussies are set to be hit harder by income taxes.

title: ‘A mockery’: Proposal for 12-table pool hall rejected by a local council
description: Sky News host Freya Leach says a proposal to set up a 12-table pool hall has been rejected by a council on the grounds that it could be a “magnet for antisocial behaviours”.   “The true crime crisis is actually a 12-table pool hall,” Ms Leach said.  “A business put in an application to a local council to set up a pool and billiards table hall … 50 residents submitted objections to this proposal, saying it could create criminal behaviours … a magnet for antisocial behaviours.”

title: ‘Growing behemoth’: Reports taxpayers could bail out NDIS providers
description: Sky News host Danica De Giorgio analyses how losses for registered NDIS providers have doubled over the past two years with taxpayers likely set to bail them out.

title: ‘It just doesn’t cut it’: Pocock highlights the secretive nature of the Albanese government
description: Independent Senator David Pocock says the Albanese government is more secretive than the Morrison government.  “It’s really frustrating because Labor and the Opposition railed against Scott Morrison’s secrecy, and then when the numbers were crunched on the last parliament, it turned out that the Albanese government was more secretive than the Morrison government,” Mr Pocock told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “It just doesn’t cut it … the last week we’ve seen them put a suppression order on a public interview with a foreign prime minister, with the Nauruan prime minister.”

title: ‘People are being fleeced’: Regions push for cheaper electricity
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond analyses how a recent motion is being pushed telling power companies to give lower bills to regions where renewable energy projects are implemented.
